If you want to store the data in-memory using a HashMap and configure it in Spring, you can create a `@Configuration` class where you define a `@Bean` for the in-memory JSON store. Here's an example:

1. Create a `JsonDataStore` class to handle the in-memory storage:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;

public class JsonDataStore {

    private ConcurrentHashMap<String, String> jsonDataMap = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void saveJsonData(String userId, String jsonData) {
        jsonDataMap.put(userId, jsonData);
    }

    public String loadJsonData(String userId) {
        return jsonDataMap.get(userId);
    }
}
```

2. Create a configuration class to define the `JsonDataStore` bean:

```java
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class JsonDataStoreConfig {

    @Bean
    public JsonDataStore jsonDataStore() {
        return new JsonDataStore();
    }

}
```

3. Autowire the `JsonDataStore` bean in your services or controllers:

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

@RestController
public class MyController {

    @Autowired
    private JsonDataStore jsonDataStore;

    @PostMapping("/saveData/{userId}")
    public void saveJsonData(@PathVariable String userId, @RequestBody String jsonData) {
        jsonDataStore.saveJsonData(userId, jsonData);
    }

    @GetMapping("/loadData/{userId}")
    public String loadJsonData(@PathVariable String userId) {
        return jsonDataStore.loadJsonData(userId);
    }

}
```

In this example, the `JsonDataStore` class will handle the in-memory storage using a ConcurrentHashMap, and the `JsonDataStoreConfig` class will define the `jsonDataStore` bean. This bean will be managed by the Spring container and can be autowired into your services or controllers, as shown in the `MyController` class.

